    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-03-20T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-03-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="439"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d439">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.85/117: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-03-20T16:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 20, 1920—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>763. R–438 for the Department and Davis. Reference your 517 March 12, 4 p.m.</p>
                <p>First. Maritime Service in London adopted March 4th, resolutions postponing
                    consideration Brazilian ship question until arrival of Brazilian delegates.<note
                        n="36" xml:id="d439fn36">The Ambassador in Brazil reported, Dec. 1, 1920:
                        “Negotiations between France and Brazil regarding German steamers seized in
                        Brazilian ports are concluded on the basis of following principles. 1. The
                        vessels now recognized as the permanent property of Brazil; 2. The
                        arrangements will be based on article 297 of the Treaty of Versailles.”
                        (File no. 832.85/124.)</note> Rathbone.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
